{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4440ff75-9314-4f0f-9129-2bf22381c094","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these locations:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates `.ips` / `.crash` files:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar for a formatted view.\n\n3. **Core dumps** — Disabled by default. To enable:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. The core file typically lands in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **`log show`** — Check the unified log for crash details:\n   ```bash\n   log show --predicate 'eventMessage contains \"your_app_name\"' --last 1h\n   ```\n\nThe **Diagnostic Reports** folder is usually the quickest win — macOS writes crash reports there automatically, no special setup required.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f1285aba-bd3a-4500-a47b-957c81eddbbf","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":294,"requestId":"D804:2F053:FBA023:120E847:69F2B532"},"id":"22bfbd28-f086-4ae0-848a-57c68f2ef518","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:49:49.080Z","parentId":"490353ed-4d0f-46ed-8509-126df7cfcd67"}
